<alan.macdonald@brunel.ac.uk> wrote:

> In article <33r2b4$qe7@news.umbc.edu> Bryan G. Olson; CMSC,
> olson@umbc.edu writes:
> >This is my second response to the same post.
> >Robert I. Eachus (eachus@spectre.mitre.org) claimed:
> >
> >If P=NP? is undecidable, then there is no proof it is undecidable. (1)
> >
> >I'd like to put this claim into one of the categories of proven,
> >disproven, or open.  So far I think it's open.  Note that if
> >P=NP is decided on either side, then claim (1) is true.
> 
> I could be missing something, but I don't see how a single
> question can be undecidable. You need a countable set of
> instances when talking about computability, just as you
> do when talking about complexity.
> 
> Al

In this context undecidable means independent of some axiom system--
such as Peano Arithmetic. For example the Continuum Hypothesis
is undecidable with respect to ZF (Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory).
The usage here does not concern decision problems-----bad, but historical
terminology.
